/**
 * @param {number[]} nums
 * @return {number}
 */
function solve(nums) {
    // The operation is: if nums[a] % nums[b] == 0, replace nums[a] with nums[b].
    // We want to minimize the sum. Replacing nums[a] with a smaller nums[b] helps minimize the sum.
    // The smallest possible value an element can be changed to is the smallest element in the array
    // that can divide it (or can divide something that divides it, recursively).

    // The key insight is that if an element x can be replaced by y (because x % y == 0),
    // then x can potentially be replaced by any element z such that y % z == 0.
    // This implies that all elements that can be reduced to a value 'd' (where 'd' is a divisor
    // of the original element, and 'd' is present in the array, or reachable) can be reduced
    // to the smallest such reachable divisor.

    // The smallest possible value any element can become is the Greatest Common Divisor (GCD)
    // of all elements that can reach it, but since we can only replace by existing elements,
    // we are looking for the smallest element 'd' that is a divisor of the current element 'x',
    // and 'd' must be reachable/present.

